<HL>
   U.S. and Japanese Officials Approach
   Trade Negotiations With Apprehension
   ----
   By John T. Norman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN GM FREST FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- In what could be the final round of
bilateral negotiations between the U.S. and Japan on
trade-related "structural" economic issues in Tokyo late this
month, U.S. officials are hoping that Japanese policy makers
won't openly advocate a new doctrine that Japan's huge
current-account and trade surpluses are desirable in
maintaining world economic stability.
   For their part, Japanese officials are apprehensive over
the amount of pressure U.S. officials might exert in the June
25-26 negotiations for more specific commitments on future
actions to open up Japanese markets for more imports and
private foreign investments.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In advance of these talks, Japanese officials are
indicating that they aren't planning to make any new
concessions to the U.S., such as making advance commitments
on the amount of planned public works spending in Japan as a
percentage of the country's gross national product.
   Japanese officials also are less than enthusiastic about
another U.S. proposal that negotiations on structural trade
issues be "institutionalized" in the form of continuing
consultations several times a year, to rehash old issues and
discuss new ones.
   Meanwhile, the new economic "theology" about the merits of
continued Japanese international trade surpluses, put forward
by some Japanese "think-tank" experts, is viewed as a
potentially troublesome issue, particularly if the Japanese
government were to openly endorse such a strategy.
   Thus far, U.S. reaction has been low-keyed, but several
top U.S. economic policy makers have said this idea lacks
merit.
   As things stand, the U.S. and Japan are slated to produce
in mid-July the final versions of their reports on policy
actions, both in Tokyo and Washington, to achieve a better
balance in trade on a longer-term basis.
   In interim reports issued in April, both governments
managed to ease some of the tensions in their bilateral trade
relations. Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu and President Bush,
who are expected to get together early next month in Houston,
ahead of the economic summit, probably will be looking for
ways to keep things on a smooth track.
                                                                                                       

   Delays in Congress: General Motors Corp. and other
companies are signing some long-term agreements to supply
equipment and technology to the Soviet Union.
   But they may have to wait until September or even longer
to know whether Congress will approve a bilateral trade
agreement to reduce U.S. tariffs on Soviet goods and, perhaps
more important, clear the way for the Export-Import Bank to
help finance exports of goods and services the Russians want
to buy.
   Separately, it also may take several months for U.S.
companies doing business with China to know, for sure, that
the U.S. will continue its "most-favored-nation" treatment
for imports of Chinese-made goods.
   The House Ways and Means international trade subcommittee,
headed by Rep. Sam Gibbons (D., Fla.) will begin hearings
June 19 on various bills designed to overturn President
Bush's decision to extend for one-year most-favored-nation
treatment for Chinese products, which means lower U.S. import
duties.
   Mr. Gibbons is promising other members of Congress, irked
over the White House decision on China, a comprehensive set
of hearings that will explore, among other things, Chinese
government policies and the impact of trade and investment
ties on the U.S., China and Hong Kong.
   Technically, Congress must decide no later than Sept. 3
whether to uphold (through inaction) or disapprove (through
legislative action) the White House China trade decision of
May 24.
   But some House members are proposing entirely new
legislation that would change the ground rules and set new
conditions for any future extensions of the U.S. tariff
concessions on imports of apparel, footwear, toys, machinery
or other products from China.
   On the Soviet Union, U.S. trade-policy officials were
saying recently they couldn't predict how soon President Bush
would formally transmit the bilateral trade agreement with
that country to Congress, coupling this with approval of
"waivers" under a 1974 Trade act to lower U.S. import duties
on Soviet exports.
   They suggested it won't happen soon because Moscow may
take several months to enact a law allowing unrestricted
emigration of Soviet residents to other countries.
   How Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev resolves Moscow's
problems with the breakaway Baltic states also will be an
important factor in this situation, according to
congressional leaders who discussed this issue with President
Bush at the White House recently.
                                                                                                       

   Credits To Finance Trade: Although the Soviet Union now is
appealing openly for credits from Western nations, including
the U.S., Moscow hasn't gotten around yet to applying for
membership in the International Monetary Fund or the World
Bank, both of which are pumping out funds to other Eastern
and Central European countries to support economic reforms.
   Last week, for example, the World Bank approved a $250
million loan to Poland to help expand natural-gas production
in that country. The bank also has assigned experts to help
Poland work out contractual arrangements to attract foreign
participation in the country's oil industry.
   While some Russian officials apparently are claiming that
they have sought informal, unofficial advice from the IMF
about currency-related issues, IMF officials say that hasn't
happened.
   In the bilateral trade agreement negotiated between the
U.S. and the Soviet Union, it was agreed that commercial
transactions between these two countries would have to be
settled in freely convertible currencies.
   In a separate "side-letter" agreement that could create
new drains on Moscow's limited holdings of dollars, the
Russians promised to begin discussions with the U.S. on
repaying about $714 million in old U.S. government loans,
after the main U.S.-Soviet trade agreement takes effect.
   U.S. officials said these old debts include $674 million
in World War II lend-lease accounts, plus $44 million the
Soviet Union still owes to the Export-Import Bank on loans
approved many years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900611-0107
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900611-0107.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Global View:
   Can the `Overseas Chinese' Remodel China?
   ----
   By George Melloan
</HL>
<DATE>
06/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   Remembrance of Tiananmen Square, that massive year-ago
uprising against the octogenarian tyrants who rule China,
inevitably leads to speculation about the country's future.
One question is whether China's communist system will be
shattered and fragmented by forces similar to those that are
breaking up the Soviet Union. There is a short answer and a
long answer.
   The short answer is that China is not the Soviet Union.
What the Soviets choose to call a "union" is in fact a
Russian empire in which some very harsh instruments of
political control have been used to force peoples of widely
varying nationalities -- from Letts to Armenians to
Moldavians to the Uzbeks -- to submit to Moscow's authority
against their will. As failed communist economic policies
have weakened Moscow's grip, its unwilling subjects have been
heading for the empire's exits.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the Chinese, it is argued, are not that way at all.
They -- particularly the Han majority -- think of themselves
as one people. So whatever happens in China, it won't be the
same thing as what is happening in the U.S.S.R.
   Well, that's a short answer, but the long answer is
different and better, in that it explores this question in
greater depth. The process of change will indeed be different
in China, but the result could be similar. The "three Chinas"
that we talk of today -- the mainland, Hong Kong and Taiwan
-- could be supplemented with some further Chinas. Among the
candidates are Guangdong and Fujian, coastal provinces now
under Beijing's control.
   For that matter, China is not totally without ethnic
diversity. Its western Moslems, not to mention the unhappy
Tibetans, have aspirations for independence not unlike those
in the restive Soviet republics. China's Moslems probably
identify more closely with the Kirghiz rebels who are
fighting Soviet security forces just across the border, or
the Kashmiris who are fighting Indian troops, than with the
Han majority in China. Islam, as we should know by now, has
significant polarizing power.
   But whereas the peoples of the west are driven by ethnic
and religious beliefs, the southeastern coastal provinces of
China are feeling the effects of something altogether
different, economic influences from abroad. Unlike China as a
whole at the moment, they have prospects for significant
economic development. That could, for a number of different
reasons, weaken the political power exercised over them from
Beijing. Their prospects for a degree of both economic and
political independence are considerably better than those of
the western or interior provinces.
   Of major importance to this process is that large and
generally affluent Asian population known as the "overseas
Chinese." These are the Chinese who among other things were
wise and foresighted enough to have left mainland China at
some point before or during the 40 years of communist rule.
Now some are going back, not to live but to look for
attractive investments. A lot of non-Chinese also have made
that search, only to be frustrated by Chinese bureaucracy or
appalled by the Tiananmen Square massacre. But the overseas
Chinese have special advantages. They know the language, the
people and the risks.
   Tiananmen Square proved that the risks are a lot higher
than many Westerners had suspected. They had overestimated
the regime's commitment to political liberalization and
underestimated its willingness to employ mass murder as an
instrument of political control. But the overseas Chinese are
among Asia's most active risk takers, willing to place their
bets early, when things look bleakest. Proof of that is the
fact that they also are putting some money into two other
benighted areas, Vietnam and Burma, apparently out of a
belief that these places too have very little choice but to
move toward political and economic liberalization.
   They have a considerable amount of money to invest. Taiwan
has almost as many dollars in its foreign reserves as Japan
-- some $75 billion. Mainland investments in the hundreds of
millions of dollars by the Taiwanese don't use up much of
that huge chunk but the amount is large by mainland standards
and growing rapidly. A great deal of it is going into Fujian
province, just across the Straits of Taiwan.
   The Hong Kong Chinese, for their part, have been steadily
developing an important economic relationship with Guangdong
province, just to their north, and with its capital Guangzhou
(known as Canton in the old days). An estimated two million
Chinese on the communist side of the border now produce
products for Hong Kong firms, and fully 70% of China's
exports to the U.S. pass through Hong Kong. Western companies
have reaped a great harvest of frustration trying to operate
joint ventures with Chinese government enterprises. Even the
Japanese have been turned off by their unhappy experiences in
China. But the Hong Kong Chinese, by focusing on the kinds of
informal, small-scale arrangements that characterize business
in Hong Kong itself, have by and large made their China
investments pay.
   Some China analysts think that strengthening business
connections with the outside world are pulling even the party
leaders in the coastal provinces away from the Beijing
party's tentacles. If that is true, it could be the origin of
a trend toward "provincialization" in China, with the
separate provinces exercising a greater degree of autonomy
than they have ever achieved in the years since the
communists came to power. The question of whether Hong Kong
might take over China in 1997 -- rather than the other way
around as currently planned -- is facetious. But it is not
out of the question that Guangdong might become more like
Hong Kong, thus representing a buffer of sorts against the
post-1997 destruction of Hong Kong's economy by mainland
communists trying to work their will on that free and
prosperous place.
   But while all this is a hopeful scenario, a very powerful
note of caution is required. The overseas Chinese themselves
are exercising due care in their investments. A good many
Hong Kong citizens are not optimistic and many have migrated
to Canada or elsewhere. There are no economic miracles yet in
Guangdong or Fujian, and there won't be until Beijing's old
men are replaced by leaders willing to make really serious
economic and political reforms. Beijing's control of both
Hong Kong and Guangdong could destroy both. Moreover, other
Chinese provinces, because of the regime's mismanagement,
face very bleak futures -- perhaps even famine -- that could
lead to a political explosion rather than evolution.
   But as the Journal's Claudia Rosett wrote on the page
opposite last week, something will have to change in China.
The anger of the huge crowds that protested in Tiananmen
Square, although suppressed with bullets, made that clear. If
you are making bets on China's future, the possibility of
provincialization, under the influence of overseas Chinese
who have learned how countries achieve economic success,
wouldn't necessarily be the worst one.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900611-0106
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900611-0106.
</DOCID>
