<HL>
   Business Brief -- Texas Instruments Inc.:
   Jobs for Defense to Be Cut
   By 1,000 Over 12 Months
</HL>
<DATE>
06/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TXN PHG
</CO>
<LP>
   Texas Instruments Inc. said it will reduce its defense
systems work force by about 1,000 employees over the next
year in response to reduced defense spending.
   The Dallas-based semiconductor and defense concern said
that all its Defense Systems and Electronics Group sites,
which employ about 22,000 people, will be affected by the
decision.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Texas Instruments said it expects the overall financial
impact from the reductions to be minimal.
   The company also announced it agreed with a unit of the
Netherlands' N.V. Philips to swap designs for a group of
computer chips called bus-interface logics.
   Under the agreement, Texas Instruments and Philips
Components-Signetics will make and sell each other's
bus-interface chips, which act as go-betweens in computers,
allowing chips to communicate with each other and to outside
equipment such as telephone lines.
   Texas Instruments estimates the world market for
bus-interface chips at about $850 million.
</TEXT>
