<LP>
   TRUMP'S MAJOR bankers agreed tentatively to lend him $50
million more and to let him suspend interest payments on
about $2 billion of debt. The developer would pledge as
security some of his remaining uncollateralized assets and
would possibly forfeit equity in other holdings. The accord,
which needs the approval of smaller creditors, would give
Trump time to improve his operations and wait out a real
estate slump.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Fed is looking into possible irregularities in the
handling and trading of U.S. bank loans to Latin America.
Improprieties may include the use of privileged information.
   ---
   Real estate seized from failed thrifts could be sold by
the government in scores of $500 million chunks under a plan
S&amp;L bailout officials are developing to speed the sale
process. Critics of the idea say the government would be
forced to offer huge price discounts to attract purchasers.
   ---
   Ames Department Stores plans to close nearly a third of
its stores and cut its staff by 18,000, or 36%. The closings
in the Midwest and the South will leave Ames, now in Chapter
11, concentrated in the Northeast.
   ---
   General Dynamics and McDonnell Douglas face probable
second-quarter write-offs because of delays in developing the
Navy's A-12 attack airplane. The Navy is reviewing the
project.
   ---
   Boeing is expected to receive today a nearly $4 billion
order from Korean Airlines for 23 jumbo jets. The deal would
be Boeing's third giant order from Asia in the past few
weeks.
   ---
   American Air won a U.S. recommendation that it fly a
coveted route from Chicago to Tokyo. The route could generate
$300 million in annual revenue. The tentative selection is a
blow to Chicago-based United Air.
   ---
   Stock prices declined Friday for the fourth day in a row.
The profit-taking focused on entertainment, retailing and
financial issues. The Dow Jones Industrial Average tumbled
34.95 points to close at 2862.38.
   ---
   U.S. brokerage firms paid a record $82,714 in compensation
per employee in 1989, despite a 26% drop in profits.
   ---
   Delays in planting grain because of the Midwest's wettest
spring in 50 years are leading some economists to predict
worsening food inflation.
   ---
   The Resolution Trust Corp. faces a test in federal court
this week over its ability to override state laws in the sale
of insolvent S&amp;Ls to banks.
                                                                                                       

   Lewis Ranieri bought the failed Murray Federal S&amp;L,
expanding his Texas thrift empire into Dallas.
   ---
   CBS is negotiating to produce programming for cable's
Discovery Channel. CBS is the only major broadcast network
without a cable venture.
   ---
   Pinnacle West's Arizona Public Service utility unit said
it will slash its work force further and revamp operations to
hold down its rates.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 142,600,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2862.38, off 34.95; transportation 1201.28, off 7.30;
utilities 212.46, off 1.45.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3422.79, off
4.57.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.55, off 0.19;
spot index 131.58, off 0.96.
   Dollar: 153.49 yen, up 0.94; 1.6975 marks, up 0.0040.
